---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug } from '../../data/posts';

const post = postBySlug('24-7-emergency-handyman-ayr')!;
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Emergency handyman',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'burst pipe Ayr', 'broken lock Ayr', 'smashed window Ayr', 'flooded drain Ayr', '24/7 handyman Ayrshire'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Ayr, Scotland' },
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        The phone going at 2.47am is usually one of five jobs. Here's what
        genuinely needs us in the van before breakfast — and what can wait.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg">
      <p>
        We run <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>a 24/7 handyman service covering Ayr</a>
        from our base 15 miles east in Sorn. That "24/7" isn't a marketing line —
        one of us, me or my dad Fraser, picks up the phone at every hour of every
        night. No call-centre, no robot, no "leave a message and we'll get back
        to you by Tuesday". So I can tell you exactly what an emergency call
        sounds like at 3am in an Ayr flat, because I take them.
      </p>
      <p>
        Not everything that feels like a crisis at midnight actually needs a
        tradesman out the door in the dark. Plenty of jobs are cheaper and safer
        to fix at 8am with proper light. But there are a handful of classics
        that genuinely do need <strong>now</strong>, not first thing, and it's
        worth knowing the difference before you're the one standing in a
        puddle looking for a phone.
      </p>

      <h2>What actually counts as a real emergency?</h2>
      <p>
        The honest test is simple: <em>is the damage getting worse every minute
        you wait?</em> If yes, it's an emergency. If you can contain it with a
        bucket, a towel or a locked internal door, it can usually wait for
        daylight and cost you less.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here are the five calls that come in most often from Ayr — the ones
        where we get boots on straight away.
      </p>

      <h3>1. Burst pipes and blown flexi hoses</h3>
      <p>
        This is the number-one out-of-hours call, hands down. A flexi hose
        under a kitchen or bathroom sink lasts about ten years, then lets go
        without warning — usually on a Saturday night. You'll know it because
        there's a fine spray of mains-pressure water hitting the inside of
        your unit and seven litres a minute going through your floor.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Do this first, before you ring anyone:</strong> find your
        stopcock and turn it off. In most Ayr flats it's under the kitchen
        sink or in a cupboard near the front door. In houses it's often in the
        garage or the cupboard where the gas meter lives. One turn clockwise.
        If you can't find it or it won't budge, ring us — we'll find it over
        the phone.
      </p>
      <p>
        Once the water is off, the emergency is over. We can be on site from
        Sorn to most Ayr postcodes inside 40 minutes. If your stopcock is
        broken or the leak is on the <em>street side</em> of the meter, that's
        a Scottish Water job and the number is 0800 0778 778 — tell the folk
        answering it's a 24-hour line.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Broken locks and front doors that won't shut</h3>
      <p>
        A house you can't lock at midnight is an emergency. A snapped UPVC
        handle, a euro-cylinder that won't turn, a slammed Yale with the key
        inside — we do the lot. I carry a set of universal UPVC handles and a
        range of euro cylinders in the van specifically because these calls
        come in at unsociable hours.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're not a locksmith — we won't pick a lock open for you if you're
        locked out of someone else's property — but if you're the owner or
        tenant and the door is yours, we'll either get it open non-destructively
        or replace the cylinder on the spot and leave you with new keys. Expect
        £70–£120 for a standard cylinder swap plus the out-of-hours surcharge.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Smashed windows</h3>
      <p>
        A smashed ground-floor window in Ayr in December is an emergency
        because the house is going to freeze and anyone walking past has an
        invitation. We can't always replace the glass at 2am (glaziers
        source-order the unit), but we can board up properly, tidy every
        shard, and book the glass in for the next working day. Think of it
        as make-safe now, proper fix tomorrow morning.
      </p>
      <p>
        If it's an upper-floor window that's gone and glass is on the street
        below, please — for the love of the postie's dog — ring 999 first so
        the footpath can be cordoned. Then ring us to make it safe.
      </p>

      <h3>4. Dead sockets and "the whole house is off"</h3>
      <p>
        We are <strong>not</strong> registered Part-P electricians, and if
        you're reading this wondering whether you can DIY a fuse-board swap,
        the answer is no. But a lot of 1am "the power's gone" calls are not
        actually electrical faults. They're the RCD tripped because the
        freezer kicked in, or a broken element in a kettle, or water in a
        socket because the wall above it has a leak.
      </p>
      <p>
        What we can do out-of-hours: isolate the circuit that's tripped,
        identify which appliance is at fault, make the house safe, and either
        bypass the offending socket or kill its breaker so the rest of the
        house stays live until a Part-P electrician gets out. That's usually
        enough to get you through the night. We have a couple of local
        Part-P guys we'll ring for you in the morning.
      </p>

      <h3>5. Blocked drains that are now flooding</h3>
      <p>
        A blocked macerator toilet, a gully that's backed up in a Saturday
        rainstorm, a kitchen sink that's sending grey water across the floor
        — these are emergencies when the water is spreading faster than you
        can mop. We carry drain rods, a wet-vac and a plunger in the van
        and we'll get it flowing.
      </p>
      <p>
        The one we <em>can't</em> fix in the dark is a collapsed mains
        sewer — that's a jet-vac tanker and a CCTV survey in daylight. But
        nine out of ten flooding drain calls in Ayr town-centre flats are
        rag-and-wipe build-ups that come out with proper equipment inside
        an hour.
      </p>

      <h2>What <em>isn't</em> an emergency?</h2>
      <p>
        Honestly? Most things. A dripping tap, a loose handle, a fence panel
        blown over, a squeaky floor, a radiator gone cold in one room, a
        patch of damp that's been there for six weeks — none of those get
        worse in the 8 hours between midnight and breakfast. Call us first
        thing, we'll book you in, and you'll pay daytime rates instead of
        the £60 out-of-hours minimum.
      </p>
      <p>
        A dripping tap loses around 5,500 litres a year at a steady drip
        [UNVERIFIED] — irritating, wasteful, worth fixing this week — but
        nothing is breaking tonight.
      </p>

      <h2>How the call actually works</h2>
      <p>
        Ring <a href={`tel:${business.phoneE164}`}>{business.phone}</a> any
        hour. Tell us the postcode and what's happening. If you can,
        <a href={`https://wa.me/${business.whatsapp.replace('+','')}`}>WhatsApp a photo or video</a>
        — it saves us both time. We'll give you a honest answer:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>"We'll be there in 40 minutes" — if it's a real emergency and we're free.</li>
        <li>"Here's what to do right now, we'll be there at 8am" — if it can be contained.</li>
        <li>"This is one for [name of trade], their number is 07…" — if it's outside our scope.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We charge a £60 minimum between 10pm and 6am. Quotes during the day
        are always free — no call-out fee anywhere in
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/troon/`}>Troon</a>, or any of
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>our East Ayrshire patch</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For non-urgent stuff,
        <a href={`${BASE}/quote/`}>send us a quote request here</a> and we'll
        come back same day. For the real 3am calls — save the number now,
        before you need it.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTABlock
    heading="Real 3am emergency in Ayr? Ring now."
    sub="One of us is already awake. Call or WhatsApp a photo — we'll tell you straight whether it needs us tonight or whether it can wait."
    location="Ayr"
  />
</BaseLayout>
